00:00:38.520 --> 00:00:46.540
So remember yesterday we looked at critical points

00:00:46.540 --> 00:00:48.220
of functions of several variables.

00:00:49.840 --> 00:00:54.360
And so a critical point of a function

00:00:54.360 --> 00:00:55.840
is a of two variables x and y.

00:01:00.440 --> 00:01:05.900
That's the point where the partial derivatives are both zero.

00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:14.900
And we've seen that there's various kinds of critical points.

00:01:15.580 --> 00:01:17.540
There's local minima.

00:01:20.120 --> 00:01:22.460
So maybe I should show the function and its contour plot.

00:01:23.460 --> 00:01:27.860
There's local maxima, which are like that,

00:01:28.140 --> 00:01:31.520
and there's settled points, which are

00:01:32.180 --> 00:01:33.580
neither minimum nor maximum.

00:01:35.600 --> 00:01:39.400
And of course, if you have a real function,

00:01:39.580 --> 00:01:41.340
then it will be more complicated.

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:43.900
